post_text:
Good Morning,
I want to update you on a few more positive cases that have been reported to us today:
One 11th grade female who is also a softball player (she's actually been in quarantine since last Sunday).
One 12th grade male who is also a football player.
One 7th grade male who is also a football player.
One elementary school teacher's aide who has not worked with any children this year and has worn a mask since day one of school starting.
I know these updates can cause anxiety for people. In my opinion, we will see cases every week for the indefinite future. I don't believe it's any different, though, in school districts throughout the country that are offering a traditional learning option. Hang in there. We'll get through this together.

post_text:
Good Afternoon, Folks,
I have decided to make a public statement regarding my decision last Sunday to quarantine the entire softball team. Even though my intentions may have been good, I made a mistake and was wrong to do it. I acted against policy that I had written and took the decision out of our parents' hands. I have called the parents of each of our softball players and apologized and have put the decision back in their hands as far as whether or not they want their children back in school. I have made this a public statement because I take the trust of our parents and community members very seriously and felt that an explanation of my actions was warranted. It's never a bad time to admit a mistake or right a wrong.

post_text:
!! UPDATE!!

We have received notification that a male sophomore student has tested positive for COVID-19. As per our guidelines and procedures, we will contact the parents/guardians of students who we can verify have been within 6ft for 15 minutes of this young man, and we will report the case to the Garvin County Health Department and the State Department of Education.. The county health department is the governing body responsible for contact tracing and recommending individual quarantine determinations. Our District policy is to quarantine the individual who has tested positive along with any siblings attending our schools. Quarantining anyone else is a parental decision.

post_text: In our continuing effort to be transparent and to give family members the opportunity to make knowledgeable decisions revolving around their children, we are informing you that we have received notification today that another high school softball player has tested positive for COVID-19. Whenever possible, we want to allow parents the opportunity to decide whether or not to quarantine their children whenever a positive case has been reported. Based on the close and frequent contact of the girls on the team, and the fact that this is the second positive case in three days, however, we have determined that it is in the best interest of the school district to quarantine the entire high school girls softball team, including coaches, in an effort to curtail the transmission of the COVID-19 virus in our student population and in our community.

post_text: I have to brag on our kids, parents and staff. We have more policies and procedures in place than ever before, and today was one of the smoothest first days of school that I have ever experienced. Parents were patient, kind, and helpful. Kids were cooperative, happy, and excited; and our staff was AMAZING in their efforts to provide a safe and caring environment for our students. Words can't adequately express the love and pride I feel for our entire Wynnewood School family. I hope our parents and community members feel like they are a part of that family because we couldn't do what we do without their help and support. I also want to say thank you to our Wynnewood Police Department for ensuring that we had a smooth start and end to our day. #YouCan'tHideThatShine! #WynnewoodStrong

post_text: DON'T FORGET... Beginning August 27, the first day of school, breakfast and/or lunch will be available for pickup for all virtual learners grades PK-12 at the Wynnewood High School cafeteria on days when school is in session. Breakfast will be available for pickup between 8:00-8:30am, and lunch pickup will be available between 11:00-11:30am. Breakfast is free of charge to all students, and lunch prices for virtual students are the same as traditional students. Parents or students picking up meals should come to the outside double doors leading into the cafeteria (southeast side of the building).

post_text: Wynnewood Public Schools is still looking to hire dependable and responsible bus monitors for the upcoming school year. We need five monitors for our morning routes, which run from 6:30-8:30am, and we need one monitor for our afternoon routes, which run approximately from 2:30-4:30pm (a couple of routes take a little longer). A background check is required and will be paid for by the district. This position pays $8.00 an hour with a start date of August 27th. This is a great part-time job opportunity. Please call the superintendents office at 405-665-2004 between 8:00am-4:00pm Monday through Friday for more information or to apply.

post_text: Wynnewood Public Schools is looking to hire dependable and responsible bus monitors for the upcoming school year. We need six monitors for our morning routes, which run from 6:30-8:30am, and we need two monitors for our afternoon routes, which run approximately from 2:30-4:30pm (a couple of routes take a little longer). A background check is required and will be paid for by the district. This position pays $8.00 an hour with a start date of August 13th. Please call the superintendents office at 405-665-2004 between 8:00am-2:00pm Monday through Thursday for more information or to apply.

post_text:
We are almost a month away from the start of school, and we know that students and their families are waiting anxiously to see what that's going to look like. The plans we were working on last week look differently than the plans we are working on this week, and quite honestly, that's been our story since late spring. We think we have it figured out, and inevitably something happens or we learn new information that causes us to rethink our plans and direction. I work with an AMAZING group of administrators, teachers, and support staff, and because of their ideas and insights, I went home last night and told my wife that I haven't felt this good in months about how school will look for us this fall. We feel that we have the big pieces of the puzzle in place; we just need another week to work through some details. It's our intention to begin rolling out our plans to everyone by the end of next week. We appreciate your patience and look forward to sharing information with you soon.

Tim Simpson
Superintendent

shared_text:
Oklahoma State Department of Education
April 29 at 1:14 PM 路

Oklahoma has climbed to third in the country for Pre-K access for 4-year-olds, according to a new report from the National Institute for Early Education Research!

Oklahoma serves 86.5% of eligible 4-year-old children (WOW! ) when public pre-kindergarten enrollment (76.3%) is combined with Head Start enrollment, the annual report states. Only the District of Columbia (87.3%) and Vermont (86.8%) serve more students.

Oklahoma has a long tradition of excellence in early childhood education and stands out in the level of professionalism and expertise of Oklahomas Pre-K teachers. Preparing our children to be ready to read by kindergarten remains a key priority here as we value the health and development of our youngest learners." - State Supt. Joy Hofmeister

Read more about Oklahoma's early childhood achievements here: https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/OKSDE/bulletins/2885053

shared_text:
NIEER.ORG
2019 - National Institute for Early Education Research

Oklahoma State Department of Education
April 27 at 9:23 AM 路

Great news about Oklahoma's early childhood initiatives from the National Institute for Early Education Research!

Oklahoma continues to lead the nation in both quality of state Pre-K and access for 4-year-olds, scoring a 9 out of 10 on the 2019 NIEER Report! 

Noteworthy highlights:

*When public pre-kindergarten (76.3%) enrollment is combined with Head Start enrollment, Oklahoma serves 86.5% of eligible 4-year-old children

*Oklahoma is one of only 5 states to meet 9 benchmarks.

*Oklahoma is one of 9 states leading in policies to support high quality standard benchmarks.

*Oklahoma received recognition for having fully aligned academic standards Pre-K to 12th grade.

April 22 at 8:46 AM 路

Oklahoma public school rock stars!!  We are eternally grateful for all school staff who are hard at work providing meals to kids during school closures.

Our schools have responded in extraordinary ways to the myriad uncertainties posed by a global pandemic. These incredible efforts by child nutrition workers and school leaders to bring millions of meals to kids since March 23 is further evidence that educators instinctively put kids first. I am thankful and humbled by their work. - State Supt. Joy Hofmeister

Let's keep the momentum going! Schools: To find out more about continuing feeding programs through the summer, contact OSDEs Office of Child Nutrition at (405) 521-3327.

JUST IN: USDE has granted preliminary approval of Oklahoma waivers allowing public school districts greater flexibility in the spending of existing federal funds.

The waivers allow schools to repurpose existing K-12 education funds for a number of COVID-19-related matters, including technology infrastructure and teacher training on distance learning. Additional flexibilities would allow schools to redirect resources to areas of highest need.

Oklahoma districts may immediately begin implementing matters authorized under the waiver. Read more:

CONTENT.GOVDELIVERY.COM
USDA approves Oklahomas request for free meals for all students

Oklahoma State Department of Education
March 30 at 3:26 PM 路

JUST IN: Oklahoma students statewide will soon be able to access two free meals a day following a USDA waiver, which was approved over the weekend after U.S. Senator James Lankford intervened.

Prior to the waiver, districts could provide free meals only if 50% of students at a school met eligibility for the free and reduced-price lunch program.

Amid such uncertainty and instability, we should not be asking our families or schools to worry over needless red tape. This waiver means that, following a simple application, any district in the state can establish feeding sites for up to two free meals a day for every student who needs one. - State Supt. Joy Hofmeister

Oklahoma State Department of Education
March 30 at 9:51 AM 路

ATTN: OKLAHOMA TEACHERS!

Hopefully, second time's the charm! 

Join us here on our Facebook page TODAY (Monday, March 30) at 2 p.m. for a Facebook Live webinar with OETA.

The webinar will provide resources and lessons to help teachers learn how to leverage OETA programming as they develop their distance learning plans.

Teachers will also be introduced to a virtual course they can access anytime to gain further support and connect with other educators who are using OETA resources.

OETA has adjusted its daytime schedule to provide curriculum-based programming for students over the air on its broadcast channel, OETA WORLD. Programs include PBS favorites like NOVA, Nature, American Experience and PBS KIDS programming.

Teachers and parents are encouraged to visit OETA.tv/LearningAtHome to view an updated program schedule, OETAs statewide channel list, curriculum and activities.

Oklahoma State Department of Education
March 26 at 3:22 PM 路

Exciting news!  We have partnered with OETA to provide in-home learning opportunities for students. The goal is to bring parents, students and teachers together with content and curriculum to meet educational needs while schools are closed due to coronavirus.

Beginning Monday, March 30, OETA will be adjusting its daytime schedule to provide curriculum-based programming for students over the air on its broadcast channel, OETA WORLD. Programs will include PBS favorites like NOVA, Nature, American Experience and PBS KIDS programming.

Programming changes to OETA WORLD will take place Monday through Friday from 6 a.m. until 6 p.m. until the end of the school year.

Teachers and parents are encouraged to visit OETA.tv/LearningAtHome to view an updated program schedule, OETAs statewide channel list, curriculum and activities.

shared_text:
Wynnewood High School
March 27 at 7:25 AM 路

From David Jackson, Executive Director of the OSSAA:

In conjunction with this decision the OSSAA Board voted unanimously, at the March 26, 2020 Teleconference Board Meeting, to cancel the State Basketball Tournament for Classes 2A, 3A, 4A, 5A and 6A; additionally, all spring activities have been cancelled for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year.

For the purpose of all OSSAA member school activities, all school personnel, including certified, adjunct or volunteer coaches, as well as teachers, directors, or instructors are prohibited from engaging in any type of OSSAA member school activity involving secondary students; no practice, instruction, training, weight lifting, tryouts, competition or travel is permitted.

SUMMER TIME ACTIVITIES: Until further notice, no OSSAA member school activities will be permitted. The timeline for the beginning of summer activities will be provided to member schools at a time when CDC recommendations as well as State and Local government recommendations allow for safe participation.

Wynnewood High School
March 22 at 3:19 PM 路

This isnt our normal Sunday after Spring Break...no getting ready for school tomorrow, no making sure the baseball uniform is clean, no setting of an alarm. I have spent much of the past few days worrying about how all of this will affect our students. Its crazy that its only been a week since weve seen them, but Ive talked to many of my teachers and they already miss them so much, way more than they probably miss us! 

With some extra time on my hands, Bobo and I took a few minutes to write a short message to our kiddos! ワ (he was about as thrilled to help me with this as my boys!)

#youcangoanywherefromhere
#hopetoaeeyousoon

shared_text:
Wynnewood Middle School Main
February 10 at 10:49 AM 路

The 6th grade Science students have been studying animal and plant cells. Friday Feb. 7th, it was their turn to put what they had learned towards a hands on approach with a little reward at the end.
Girls were instructed to make animal cells while the boys concentrated on plant cells. Using food related items they took basic candies and incorporated them into organelles found within each type of cell and recorded information. Eating the "cell" was the highlight of the lesson. We are so proud of the effort and creativity projected by the students, but most of all, the patience before eating! Way to go kids!

On Friday, January 17 we will crown our 2020 Basketball Homecoming King and Queen. Our candidates, pictured below, are Seniors Danchez Patterson and Caitlin Harmon, Sophomores Moses Gibson and Seezan Thompson, and Juniors Zack Ray and Jaidyn Delatorre.

We will be having a pep assembly at 2:20 pm in the high school gym. Coronation will be at 5:45 pm. For this night, the boys team will play first beginning at 6:30 pm, followed by the girls! It is sure to be a fun night! The Proud Sound of Wynnewood will also be at the game to get us pumped up!

The holidays are upon us and as much as wed like to think that everyone enjoys these special times, we understand that there can be great burdens for our students to deal with on top of their daily lives. We want to reach out and remind our families to make sure you are aware that Jetty Counseling service is available through the school, to assist our students with issues that may seem too large for them to process. If you feel that your child could benefit from this counseling service, please do not hesitate to call the school at 665-4105. Our students physical, mental and academic well being is our top priority.

post_text: After investigating the situation revolving around the hit list found at the Middle School, School administration feels confident that the issue has been resolved and that our students are safe from this threat. Thank you for your cooperation and patience.
text: After investigating the situation revolving around the hit list found at the Middle School, School administration feels confident that the issue has been resolved and that our students are safe from this threat. Thank you for your cooperation and patience.

post_text: All district students and staff: This message is to inform you that a hit list has been found at our Middle School today. Police are on site and have made a precautionary sweep of the building. The parents or guardians of the students identified on the list have been notified. We are working to determine the origin of the list. The safety of our students is our top priority, and while it is not our intention to cause panic or anxiety, we feel it is important to keep our families apprised of situations such as this.
